A good structure is a small command-loop adventure where each GitHub workflow step is a potion-making action, and the player learns the sequence by doing it in order. You can model it as scenes, inventory, step validation, and a win condition.

Core game loop
Use a simple terminal loop:

Show the current objective.

Accept one command from the player.

Check whether the command matches the next workflow step.

Advance the story or give feedback.

Repeat until the potion is finished.

This works well because the workflow in the file is naturally sequential: fork, clone, branch, change, commit, push, PR.

Story mapping
Map each GitHub action to a brewing metaphor:

Fork the repo → Copy the recipe scroll into your own notebook.

Clone your fork → Bring the notebook into your workshop.

Create a branch → Prepare a separate cauldron for this experiment.

Make changes → Add herbs, stir, adjust the brew.

Commit your changes → Seal the current potion state in a vial.

Push to your fork → Send the vial back to your home shelf.

Open a Pull Request → Ask the guild master to inspect the potion.

That mapping keeps the fantasy consistent while preserving the real workflow meaning.

Game structures
A basic implementation could use these data structures:

GameState: current step, inventory, completed steps, dialogue log.

Step: id, title, expected command, success text, failure text.

Item: herb names, vial, notebook, cauldron.

Scene: intro text, available actions, next scene id.

Validation: checks whether the player used the right action in the right order.

For example, the “create branch” step might require the player to have the notebook copied and the cauldron prepared before allowing the next action.

Terminal flow
A clean terminal screen might look like this:

text
Potion Quest: GitHub Alchemy

You stand before the recipe table.
Goal: Learn the workflow by brewing the potion.

Current step: Fork the repo
Hint: Make your own copy first.

> fork scroll
You copy the recipe into your own notebook.
Next step: Clone your fork
Each step should give one short clue and one clear success message, so the player can infer the workflow without getting lost.

Teaching design
To make it educational, reinforce each step with both action and explanation. For example, after “commit your changes,” show something like: “You seal this version so you can return to it later.” That ties the metaphor back to the Git concept instead of leaving it purely symbolic.

You can also add:

A “mistake” system that explains why steps are out of order.

A journal that records each Git action and its meaning.

A final recap that lists the full workflow in plain language.

Minimal implementation shape
At minimum, you only need:

A linear sequence of 7 steps.

A command parser.

State tracking for progress.

Success/failure text.

A final completion screen.

A tiny terminal game with those pieces is enough to teach the GitHub workflow clearly while still feeling like a potion-brewing adventure.
